    <h2>The 4.0 GPA Scale Explained</h2>
    <p>The most widely used grading system in American colleges and universities is the 4.0 scale. Each letter grade you receive in a course corresponds to a specific number of grade points. An A earns 4.0 points, a B earns 3.0 points, a C earns 2.0 points, a D earns 1.0 point, and an F earns 0 points. Many schools also use plus and minus modifiers that adjust these values slightly, though exact values can vary by institution.</p>
    <p>The 4.0 scale creates a standardized way to compare academic performance across different courses, semesters, and institutions. Whether you take an introductory English class or an advanced organic chemistry course, both grades are converted to the same numerical scale before being averaged together. This simplicity is both a strength and a limitation of the system — it treats all courses equally regardless of difficulty, which is why some schools and programs use weighted GPAs for more nuanced evaluations.</p>

