    <p>Note that some schools award a 4.3 for an A+, while others cap it at 4.0. Always check your institution's specific grading policy. Use our <a href="/education-calculators/gpa-calculator/">GPA calculator</a> to quickly compute your GPA using your school's exact scale.</p>

    <h2>Understanding Quality Points and Credit Hours</h2>
    <p>The two building blocks of every GPA calculation are <strong>quality points</strong> and <strong>credit hours</strong>. Credit hours represent the weight or workload of a course — a typical lecture course is 3 credit hours, while labs are often 1 credit hour and intensive seminars may be 4 or 5 credit hours. Quality points are calculated by multiplying the grade points you earned in a course by the number of credit hours that course is worth.</p>
    <p>For example, if you earn a B (3.0 grade points) in a 4-credit course, your quality points for that course are 3.0 multiplied by 4, which equals 12.0 quality points. If you earn an A (4.0 grade points) in a 3-credit course, your quality points are 4.0 multiplied by 3, which equals 12.0 quality points. Notice that even though the B course had a lower grade, the equal quality points show why credit hours matter — a higher-credit course has more influence on your GPA.</p>
    <p>This weighting system means that a poor grade in a 4-credit course will drag your GPA down more than a poor grade in a 1-credit course. Conversely, earning an A in a high-credit course gives your GPA a larger boost. Strategic course selection — understanding which courses carry more credits and where your strengths lie — can be an important part of GPA management.</p>

    <h2>How to Calculate Your Semester GPA: Step by Step</h2>
    <p>Calculating your semester GPA involves three straightforward steps. Let us work through a complete example using a typical college semester schedule.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 1: List your courses, credit hours, and letter grades.</strong> Write down each course you completed during the semester along with its credit hours and the letter grade you received.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 2: Convert letter grades to grade points and calculate quality points.</strong> For each course, multiply the grade points by the credit hours to get quality points.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 3: Divide total quality points by total credit hours.</strong> This gives you your semester GPA.</p>

    <h3>Worked Example: Fall Semester</h3>
    <p>Suppose a student takes five courses in the fall semester with the following results:</p>
